.\" ###### Setup ############################################################
.Dd April 20, 2026
.Dt unixts2time 1
.Os unixts2time
.\" ###### Name #############################################################
.Sh NAME
.Nm unixts2time
.Nd converts an Unix timestamp to a time string
.\" ###### Synopsis #########################################################
.\" Manpage syntax help:
.\" https://forums.freebsd.org/threads/howto-create-a-manpage-from-scratch.13200/
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm unixts2time
.Op unix_timestamp
.br
.Op Fl F | Fl Fl float
.Op Fl I | Fl Fl integer
.br
.Op Fl H | Fl Fl human-readable
.br
.Op Fl s | Fl Fl seconds
.Op Fl m | Fl Fl milliseconds
.Op Fl u | Fl Fl microseconds
.Op Fl n | Fl Fl nanoseconds
.Nm unixts2time
.Op Fl h | Fl Fl help
.Nm unixts2time
.Op Fl v | Fl Fl version
.\" ###### Description ######################################################
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm unixts2time
converts an Unix timestamp to a time string in the format
%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.SSSSSSSSS. The Unix timestamp is the time (nanoseconds,
microseconds, milliseconds, or seconds) since the Unix Epoch, i.e. Jaunary 1,
1970, 00:00:00.000000000 UTC.
.br
By default, the timestamp-granularity is
auto-detected using the following heuristic:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It
Seconds (s): from
0 (1970-01-01 00:00:00) to 4999999999 = 5e9-1 (2128-06-11 08:53:19), and
-1 (1969-12-31 23:59:59) to -4999999999 = -5e9 (1811-07-23 15:06:41);
.It
Milliseconds (ms): from
5000000000 = 5e9 (1970-02-27 20:53:20,000) to 4999999999999 = 5e12-1 (2128-06-11 08:53:19,999), and
-5000000000 = -5e9 (1969-11-04 03:06:40,000) to -4999999999999 = -5e12-1 (1811-07-23 15:06:410,999);
.It
Microseconds (µs) from
5000000000000 = 5e12 (1970-02-27 20:53:20,000000) to 4999999999999999 = 5e15-1 (2128-06-11 08:53:19,999999), and
-5000000000000 = 5e12 (1969-11-04 03:06:40,000000) to -4999999999999999 = 5e15-1 (1811-07-23 15:06:410,999999);
.It
Nanoseconds (ns) from
5000000000000000 = 5e15 (1970-02-27 20:53:20,000000000), and
-5000000000000000 = 5e15 (1969-11-04 03:06:40,000000000).
.El
That is, unless using dates around 1969/1970, ancient past, or distant future, the auto-detection should work reasonably well. Optionally, the timestamp granularity can be specified explicitly.
.Pp
.\" ###### Arguments ########################################################
.Sh ARGUMENTS
The following options are available:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It unix_timestamp
The Unix timestamp to be converted. If not provided, the current system time is used.
.It Fl F | Fl Fl float
Parse the Unix timestamp as a floating-point number.
.It Fl I | Fl Fl integer
Parse the Unix timestamp as an integer number.
A prefex of 0x is interpreted as hexadecimal (base 16),
a prefex of 0 is interpreted as octal (base 8).
Otherwise, the number is interpreted as decimal (base 10).
.It Fl H | Fl Fl human-readable
Provide the output in human-readable form. Default: off.
.It Fl s | Fl Fl seconds
The Unix timestamp is given in seconds. Default is auto-detection (see above).
.It Fl m | Fl Fl milliseconds
The Unix timestamp is given in milliseconds. Default is auto-detection (see above).
.It Fl u | Fl Fl microseconds
The Unix timestamp is given in microseconds. Default is auto-detection (see above).
.It Fl n | Fl Fl nanoseconds
The Unix timestamp is given in nanoseconds. Default is auto-detection (see above).
.It Fl h | Fl Fl help
Prints command-line parameters.
.It Fl v | Fl Fl version
Prints program version.
.El
.\" ###### Examples #########################################################
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It unixts2time
.It unixts2time --human-readable
.It unixts2time --human-readable --seconds 1773744755
.It unixts2time --human-readable --seconds -- -1000000
.It unixts2time --human-readable --milliseconds -- -442460258000
.It unixts2time --human-readable --seconds 1773736279
.It unixts2time -s 1773736279
.It unixts2time --milliseconds 212847000000
.It unixts2time -H 212847008123456789
.It unixts2time 0x179cb2ae8af3dd89
.It unixts2time -H 0x179cb2ae8af3dd89
.It LC_NUMERIC=en.UTF-8 unixts2time -Fs 212847123.123
.It LC_NUMERIC=de_DE.UTF-8 unixts2time -Fs 212847123,123456789
.It unixts2time --version
.It unixts2time --help
.El
